[2] California (Marin County prison)
Date: Fri 28 Aug 2015
Source: Los Angeles Times [edited]
http://www.latimes.com/local/political/la-me-water-shut-off-as-san-quentin-prison-strives-to-stop-spread-of-deadly-bacteria-20150828-story.html


Officials turned off the water at San Quentin State Prison on Friday, 28 Aug 2015, and temporarily trucked in portable toilets after an inmate was hospitalized with Legionnaires' disease and more than 2 dozen other prisoners showed signs of the illness.

The state corrections department, in conjunction with medical and health department staff, then began a hunt for the source of the bacterial infection, which can cause severe and sometimes fatal pneumonia. Fortunately, "Legionnaires' is not an infectious disease -- it cannot be transmitted person to person," said Joyce Hayhoe, a spokeswoman for the medical receiver's office that runs prison healthcare services in California. "It is transmitted through aerosolized water or inhaling contaminated soil."

State corrections spokeswoman Dana Simas said some 30 inmates at the Marin County prison -- the state's oldest -- were under observation Friday, 28 Aug 2015, with for pneumonia-like symptoms. 1 inmate who tested positive for the bacteria on Thu, 27 Aug 2015, remained hospitalized in stable condition, Simas said. 2 others also were hospitalized but had not been officially diagnosed with Legionnaires' disease. No staff members were reported sick with the bacteria.

In the meantime, prison officials ordered a halt to visitation and shut off water to the more than 3700 inmates and 1800 workers at the 163-year-old lockup. They brought in water trucks, bottled water and 100 portable toilets. On the advice of public health experts, the prison decided by late Friday afternoon, 28 Aug 2015, to allow inmates to again use the toilets in their cells, and to permit cooking with tap water.

California public health records show 348 reported cases of Legionnaires' disease in 2014, 2/3 of them affecting individuals 65 or older. More than half of the cases occurred in Los Angeles County.

From 2009 to 2012, California reported 82 deaths attributed to the bacterium, according to the state Department of Public Health.

[Byline: Paige St. John]

